snippet.title: How much does a full time rower get paid!
snippet.description:
I appreciate this video is a lot if talking and information. 
I threw a sweet crossfit workout in at 12:01 
I hope it provides some personal insight into what it's is like financially as a full time athlete. 
insta @philipdoyle2
sorry for the noise of the bike

All the information can be found on Sport Ireland website
All athletes funding is published every year and is free to view. If you google "Sport Ireland athlete carding" you will find the guidelines, how to apply and who gets what.

From PR3 Singles to Open Eights, from school dominance to club pride - this was Australian rowing at its finest.

#ARC25 wasn‚Äôt just a regatta - it was a statement. Relive the action in our wrap reel and get ready, because the road to Shanghai has officially begun.

üèÜ #ARC25 Club Winners üèÜ

Sydney Rowing Club has done it again, claiming the Champion Club Point Score at #ARC25! With powerhouse performances across the regatta, they topped the leaderboard in dominant style.

üëè Congratulations to all clubs who lit up Lake Barrington and brought the energy to this year‚Äôs Championships. Here's how the final pointscore stacked up:

ü•á Sydney Rowing Club ‚Äì 356.78
ü•à Melbourne University Boat Club ‚Äì 175.93
ü•â Mercantile Rowing Club ‚Äì 173.3

snippet.title: Beyond the Dream - Race To Paris
snippet.description:
Australia‚Äôs Olympic trials for rowing are among the most brutal of any sport. They have never been open to the public or media.

Until now.

In a television first, take a front row seat as some of Australia‚Äôs finest athletes put it all on the line in the Race To Paris. Hearts are broken and dreams come true as would-be Rowsellas push it to the limit and beyond.

It‚Äôs rowing like you‚Äôve never seen before.

Don't miss it. 8pm AEST July 22 exlusively on Channel 9 & 9Now. 

Channel 9 & 9Now is your home of #Paris2024 in Australia.
#9WWOS #Olympics

snippet.title: Webinar: Safety - Before, During & After
snippet.description:
Everyone involved in rowing has a duty of care to ensure their actions both on and off the water are conducted in a manner which does not compromise the safety of others. Rowing Ireland has the responsibility to develop and maintain a culture of safe practice to advise all our clubs that they can support everyone involved in the sport in their efforts to achieve this.

All decisions regarding safety at rowing clubs and rowing events should be based on risk management as no safety document can possibly cover all situations. By continually assessing likely risks and taking action to manage them, some generalised standards can be developed, enabling us to provide guidance on how to avoid and take action regarding unforeseen hazardous situations.

All clubs have a responsibility to provide information, education and training about safety to their members. Individual members also have a responsibility to find out, learn, question and implement safety best practice. It is essential that all clubs register their members with Rowing Ireland to ensure full cover for all members. In addition, clubs need to take into account their own local risks and should conduct risk assessments regularly.

Having safety in mind at all times is an important part of what it means to be a club member.

For further information please contact info@rowingireland.ie

snippet.title: Inniscarra Lake, at the National Rowing Centre in Farran, County Cork
snippet.description:
Inniscarra Lake, at the National Rowing Centre in Farran, County Cork, is the premier venue for rowing in Ireland. Created as a reservoir in the 1950s, the lake is famous as the training ground for Irish Olympic Gold medalists Paul O'Donovan and Fintan McCarthy, as well as Bronze medalists Daire Lynch and Philip Doyle, all from the Paris 2024 Games. Surrounded by lush greenery and serene waters, Inniscarra provides the perfect setting for team-building days, making it an ideal location for groups seeking a unique and inspiring experience.

Email: Communications@Rowingireland.ie

At Rowing Ireland, we‚Äôve all been influenced by incredible women ‚Äì whether it‚Äôs a coach, teammate, mentor, or family member who has supported us along the way. To celebrate International Women‚Äôs Day, we asked our athletes: Who has been the biggest female influence in your life, and why?

As we embrace this year‚Äôs #IWD2025 theme of accelerating action, recognising the women who paved the way for progress is essential.

üö£ Andrew Sheehan ‚Äì U23 Medallist

üö£ Fintan McCarthy ‚Äì 2-Time Olympic Champion
üö£ Natalie Long ‚Äì Olympian
üö£ Fin O‚ÄôReilly ‚Äì U23 Medallist

This International Women‚Äôs Day, we celebrate the role models, mentors, and supporters who continue to break barriers and inspire the next generation. Let‚Äôs accelerate action and create more opportunities for women in sport.

snippet.title: Rowing Ireland X Coillte Partnership
snippet.description:
Rowing Ireland are delighted to announce a new partnership with Coillte.

Rowing Ireland's state-of-the-art Training Centre, located in Farran Forest Park, Co. Cork, one of Coillte's 12 forest parks nationwide, is a central hub for nurturing Ireland's growing elite rowing talent and preparing athletes for domestic and international competitions since 2007.

snippet.title: Energy Availability Webinar
snippet.description:
Dr Sharon Madigan hosted a webinar on energy availability. Sharon works with the Sport Ireland Institute and has a wealth of experience working with athletes of all levels, including our own High-Performance rowers. 

Having worked with low energy availability athletes, she is very aware of the warning signs and their effects.

Sharon also interviews High-Performance Athletes Lydia Heaphy and Philip Doyle.

snippet.title: Rowing Ireland: Come join us on our journey
snippet.description:
Rowing Ireland has released a new video highlighting the hard work and dedication of their whole team. 

The video recognises the hardships that have been brought about by the pandemic and how it touched the lives of so many.

Paying tribute to the last 16 months since the pandemic began. It features Ireland‚Äôs top rowing athletes and their return to the water after restrictions eased earlier this year.

Rowing Ireland‚Äôs CEO, Michelle Carpenter said, ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs great to finally return to domestic and International rowing and to have such an exciting time ahead for all our athletes. We‚Äôve all been touched by the pandemic in different ways, and we wanted to mark the progress we‚Äôve made together with the dedication and resilience of all our clubs and athletes.

‚ÄúWhile it‚Äôs been tough for our rowers, I have no doubt that their preparation will pay off. We have a great team here at Rowing Ireland, not only the athletes but our coaches, clubs, families and support staff too.‚Äù

Support our athletes

You can support our athletes this summer and for our development athletes with our new Supporter T-shirts and other stock including a new line arriving next week.

Shop: www.greenblades.ie

Irish Team Competing at the 2020 Tokyo Olympics

The Women's Single Scull (Sanita Puspure) and Men‚Äôs Double Sculls (Ronan Byrne and Phil Doyle) will be the first of the Irish crews competing at the  Olympics which takes place in the early hours of Friday morning.

Ireland has six crews competing in Tokyo, the largest Irish rowing team to ever compete. 

Full coverage of the Olympic Rowing events will be available on www.rowingireland.ie and through the Rowing Ireland social media channels

snippet.title: Go with the Flow Webinar
snippet.description:
Rowing Ireland hosted a Go with the Flow webinar with Dr. Sharon Madigan and Dr. Katie Lydon on the impact of the menstrual cycle on athletes and how best to support them.

Dr. Katie Lydon, is the Dublin Ladies Team Doctor and a Sport Ireland Researcher on the topic of PMS in athletes. Katie discusses the menstrual cycle and management of issues, such as treatment options and areas of concern (loss of cycle).

Dr. Sharon Madigan is the Head of Performance Nutrition with the Sport Ireland Institute. Sharon discusses the link between fuel, training load, and the effects on menstrual health.

This is an important topic for both coaches and athletes and we encourage both to watch.

snippet.title: GB Rowing Team Paralympic Squad: Frankie's Story
snippet.description:
Frankie started rowing at aged 12. From there she went on to row at Pangbourne College and later continued her rowing development at Oxford Brookes University alongside studying for her Physiotherapy BSc. During this time Frankie discovered that her disability, Erb‚Äôs palsy, was classifiable for Paralympic rowing. Shortly after starting University, Frankie trialled for the GB Para Rowing Team and was selected for the PR3 mixed coxed four for the 2022 season.

She qualified her boat for the 2024 Paris Paralympics in 2023 and is on track to race in this undefeated boat this summer üí™

snippet.title: GB Rowing Team Paralympic Squad | Gregg Stevenson's story
snippet.description:
Gregg Stevenson became a double amputee after a blast injury whilst on patrol in Afghanistan in 2009. After joining the GB Rowing Team in 2023, he‚Äôs now a record-holding World and European Champion and has qualified his boat for the Paralympics next year üí™

Paralympic impairments can range from restricted ankle or wrist movements to spiral injuries, amputations and more. If you think you (or anyone you know!) has what it takes to join the squad, fill in our easy form to get started!

snippet.title: R0W31 2023 | Live Workout Week 4
snippet.description:
It's week 4 of #ROW31 2023 but there's still plenty of time to sign up for the programme and complete your workouts in your own time. 

The session:
Warm up = 4 minutes
Session = 10 x 1 minute on, 1 minute off
Cooldown = 3 minutes light row and stretch

ROW31 is an easy-to-follow workout programme for all abilities, is completely free to join and takes just 30 seconds to sign up. 

Find out more about the programme and sign up for your daily January workout here üëá

snippet.title: 2021 European Rowing Championships, Varese, Italy - Wrap-up
snippet.description: Exactly six months on from the 2020 edition, the 2021 European Rowing Championships in Varese, Italy provided thrilling racing and a strong sense that we are in for an exciting season leading towards the Olympic and Paralympic Games. Great Britain was absent from the 2020 European Championships, but demonstrated that they had been training hard as they topped the 2021 medal table with 12 medals. Home nation Italy were second in the final medal standings, with the Netherlands in third.

snippet.title: How to Find Out What Platform a Website Is Using
snippet.description:
How to Find Out What Platform a Website Is Using

Determining a website's platform involves a few simple techniques. Begin by right-clicking on the webpage and selecting "View Page Source." Look for clues within the code, such as comments mentioning specific platforms (e.g., "Powered by WordPress") or file paths indicating particular systems. Alternatively, use online tools like BuiltWith or Wappalyzer, which analyze a website and identify its underlying technologies, including the CMS, frameworks, and server-side languages. Browser extensions like Wappalyzer offer real-time platform detection. Remember that some websites may intentionally obscure this information, so complete accuracy isn't always guaranteed.

--------------

Video link: https://youtu.be/kguy7MY9D7M
Channel link: https://www.youtube.com/@HeyInsights

Have questions or thoughts? Leave a comment below. Thank you! üòÉ

snippet.title: How To Add Website In Google Search Console 2025 | Submit Website To Google Search Console
snippet.description:
Learn How To Add Website In Google Search Console in 2025. I‚Äôll show you step by step how to submit website to google search console in minutes. Whether you want to add WordPress website in google search console or you want to add blogger website in google search console this video is perfect for you.

 In This Video Tutorial You‚Äôll Learn:
1. How To Add Website In Google Search Console 2025
2.  How To Submit Website To Google Search Console

Follow the simple steps To Add Website In Google Search Console:

Step #1: Access Google Search Console Account
Go to Google.com and search for "Google Search Console," click on the first result, and select "Start now." This will take you to the Google Search Console dashboard.

Step #2: Add Website In Google Search Console
Enter your website URL and click "Continue," then verify ownership by adding the verification code to your website, and click "Verify" to successfully add your website to Google Search Console.

That‚Äôs it you have successfully submitted your website to google search console.

snippet.title: Rowing SA Season 2021-22 Update Video - REVISED
snippet.description:
**Revision includes information about the AGM and the correct process of constitutional amendments. The initial statement about a Special General Meeting occurring immediately following the AGM has been withdrawn. Depending on feedback following the AGM discussions, along with further consultation, a Special General Meeting may be called once we are in a position to put forward the proposed updates of the Constitution. Apologies for the confusion.**

Here's an update with what's going on around South Australian Rowing!

- Club video time - show us what your clubs are up to - get them online by Thursday 26th August to have your video updated on the website
- 2021 AGM set for 6:30pm in the Lakeside Function room at the Lakes hotel on Monday the 30th August. Be there - details: https://rowingsa.asn.au/annual-general-meetings/
- Regatta season dates are up - block them out and get involved!
- Coastal Rowing come and try's will be back when the weather warms up
- More details on the SA Indoor Rowing Series will come, but the AIRC is locked in for the 30th October! https://rowingaustralia.com.au/.../australian-indoor.../
- State Team proceedings are kicking off with STSP nominations now open. Link on the website.
- Keep training and being kind to one another! #YeahSA

snippet.title: 4 8K TIME TRIAL 2021
snippet.description:
4.8k Time trial briefing video for first-timers! 

Rules are simple:
-Get your bow numbers from the Regatta Control
-Boat efficiently and be kind to one another
-Row up to the start around the back of the island - eyes up for other craft
-Keep to your bowside at all times - middle or bowside arch when rowing through bridges, even when racing
-No rowing in the Dragon boat area, noted by the coloured buoys in the Northern Basin
-Ensure you are marshalled and ready at least 5 minutes before your start time.
-Look out for the bridges!
-Yield to the faster crew - they get right of way. Less than 50m distance gap is the time when you need to make moves to get out of the way of the faster boat.
-Race up the course in lanes 1, 2, or 3
-Stop and help anyone in trouble
-Follow all instructions given by BRO's and volunteers
-Have fun!

snippet.title: Week 3 - Know your waterways (Part 1)
snippet.description:
Here we talk about general waterway rules for rowers and how to stay safe! We address:

1. Traffic flow / Circulation pattern maps for all RSA venues (Torrens and West Lakes) are on our website and should be in all rowing sheds

2. To stay safe you should:
- Know the traffic flow pattern
- Only row on the correct side of the waterway
- Look around every few 100m
- Call out if you see a collision about to occur
- Check your path before stopping or turning
- Give faster boats right of way

3. Report any on-water incidents, near misses and off-water incidents by submitting an incident report form (see the RSA website). 


https://rowingsa.asn.au/safety-information/

snippet.title: Week 2 - Know yourself and your equipment
snippet.description:
To ensure your training and racing runs smoothly and to avoid dangerous situations with malfunctioning equipment, Rowing SA have provided this "how-to" to help manage yourselves and your equipment in the safest way possible so that we can have an incident and boat-damage free season!

The 3 steps are: 
- Risk assessment
- Athlete competency check
- Equipment check

All details of safety requirements and policies can be found here:
https://rowingsa.asn.au/safety-information/ 
https://rowingsa.asn.au/rowing-sa-policies/

snippet.title: Introduction to Safety Month. Week 1 - SAFE PEOPLE AND PLACES
snippet.description:
Rowing SA are passionate about keeping our membership safe and promoting a positive environment within the community. We will run out a 5-week intensive with a different focus on each week to ensure educate the membership and ensure compliance through all aspects of our rowing programs and promote a safer and more positive atmosphere within the community.

Keep your eye out while we provide resources for how together we can make rowing in SA a safer and more inclusive community.

snippet.title: Refresher on how to properly sanitise the erg when you're done!
snippet.description:
As we can now re-open our Indoor Rowing Room and with our gyms also being used, it's super important to keep our machines properly sanitised to stop the spread of COVID and any other nasty germs. Super basic, but unfortunately there have been times when the machines have been left in an unsatisfactory manner. A quick refresher to ensure we're all on the same page!

Take care of our equipment, respect the space by keeping it clean and tidy and we'll keep providing the service :)

Remember it's first in-best dressed with the booking system - don't assume that you can walk in and use the room.

Check availablility and book the Rowing SA Indoor Rowing Room here: https://www.picktime.com/rowingsaindoorrowingroom

snippet.title: BIG K'S CHALLENGE
snippet.description:
BETWEEN 15TH AND 21ST OF JUNE GET INVOLVED IN THE "BIG K'S CHALLENGE"!

All kms of travel by BOAT, ERG, FOOT or BIKE will count for points ‚Äì so long as they‚Äôre recorded on STRAVA and submitted at the end of the week! The points will be allocated as follows: 

1KM ROW = 1 POINT 

1KM ERG = 1.5 POINTS 

1.5KM WALK/RUN = 1 POINT 

BONUS 1 POINT PER 50M ELEVATION BY FOOT 

3KMS CYCLE = 1 POINT 

BONUS 1 POINT PER 100M ELEVATION BY BIKE 

 

How do I win the 10 bonus points?  

There will be 10 bonus points for each category for the most KMs completed by pulling handle (Boat/erg), by foot (walk/run) and by bike. DON‚ÄôT FORGET TO SUBMIT YOUR TOTALS! 

ALL DETAILS ON THE WEBSITE: https://rowingsa.asn.au/12-week-development-program/ 


DISCLAIMER:

Rowing SA‚Äôs fitness challenges are for educational purposes only and is not to be interpreted as a recommendation for a specific treatment plan, training program, product or course of action. You should consult your physician or other health care professional before following these sessions or any fitness program to determine if it is appropriate for you. The use of any information provided via the 12 week program is solely at your own risk.

 

Rowing SA does not warrant or represent that the fitness challenges are free from human or mechanical error, technical inaccuracies or other errors or defects. Any exercise program may result in injury. 

 

By voluntarily undertaking any exercises displayed on this website you assume the risk of any resulting injury. Rowing SA disclaims any liability from and in connection with the 12 week development program.

snippet.title: Dr Amber Halliday shares insight into being a successful athlete
snippet.description:
Dr Amber Halliday talks about how to take the next step in sport, giving personal insight into everyday training, how to stay balanced and everything rowing. Some great insights into lightweight rowing, how to successfully move up through age categories, teamwork and how to manage your headspace to avoid injuries and go fast.  

Amber has phenomenal insight to selections, rowing with different people and pushing yourself. To access her online course in She Thrives in Sport (and an AWESOME DISCOUNT!) head to https://www.shethrivesinsport.com/ and email Amber at shethrivesinsport@gmail.com for the special discount she is giving to the SA Rowing community until the end of June!

#YeahSA

snippet.title: Steady State Rowing Workout | Build Power and Efficiency at Low Stroke Rates (18-22 SPM)
snippet.description:
üö£ Build Rowing Power at Low Rates | Pyramid Workout üö£

Are you struggling to generate real power at lower stroke rates (18-22 SPM)? Today's rowing workout is specifically designed to boost your connection, torque, and overall rowing power at these essential low rates. Ideal for anyone from beginner to seasoned rower aiming for stronger steady-state sessions and improved rowing efficiency.

Workout Details:

Warm-up: 5 minutes pick drill + 5 minutes paddling (with short bursts)

Main Workout: Power Pyramid

2 mins at 18 SPM

2 mins at 20 SPM

2 mins at 22 SPM

2 mins at 20 SPM

2 mins at 18 SPM

Cool down: 5-10 minutes easy rowing and stretching

Why this Workout?
This structured power pyramid workout helps you learn how to maintain consistent power across varying stroke rates, setting a strong foundation for higher intensity pieces. Perfect for improving your steady-state rowing, and developing better biomechanics.

üîó Related Blog Post: https://www.coachbergenroth.com/steady-state-rowing-on-the-erg-low-rate-high-power-workouts-explained/

üìà Key Benefits:

Improved connection and torque at lower stroke rates

Enhanced rowing efficiency and power

Better cardiovascular training through controlled intensity

Establishing a solid technique foundation for higher stroke rates

Equipment Used:

Concept2 Rowing Machine

Heart rate monitor

ErgZone App for real-time metrics tracking

snippet.title: Understanding Critical Power for Rowers - Individualizing Rowing Training Plans
snippet.description:
In this video, we dive deep into Critical Power, exploring what it is, how to accurately calculate it, and why it's essential for personalized rowing training programs. As an experienced rowing coach, I'll share my journey integrating Critical Power into my coaching practice, illustrating how understanding this key metric allows for precise training intensity individualization. Learn about anaerobic work capacity (W') and see practical examples of power-duration tests (3-minute and 12-minute max wattage tests) that help establish accurate athlete profiles. This comprehensive guide will explain the science behind Critical Power, clarify the relationship between aerobic and anaerobic systems, and demonstrate how to apply this knowledge to optimize interval workouts and enhance performance. Whether you're a competitive rower, coach, or simply passionate about sports science and performance optimization, this video will equip you with actionable insights and the tools you need to tailor your rowing workouts effectively.

#CriticalPower #RowingTraining #AnaerobicCapacity #SportsScience #RowingCoach #PerformanceOptimization #IntervalTraining #RowingWorkouts #PowerZones #TrainingTips

https://www.coachbergenroth.com/understanding-critical-power-a-key-metric-for-rowers-performance-and-training/

snippet.title: How to Steady State Row Correctly - 5 x 8 Minute Technical Rowing Session.
snippet.description:
How to steady state properly. A mistake that a lot of athletes make is going too hard on steady state.

In this video I run through a 40 minute steady state training session and demonstrate a few important topics.

1) Rowing technically well and meta-cognitively engaging while rowing. 
2) Keeping heart rate within the 70% +/- zone for effective steady state rowing. 
3) Integrating drills into steady state rowing. 
4) Discussing the advantages/disadvantages of catch drills and why you should follow up with the pick drill after doing catch drills. 

The app featured in this video is currently in beta testing and my clients are using it to facilitate programming and data transfer their training plans. If you wish to use my public app Remote Rowing Coach, you can find it here on the iOS app store. 
https://apps.apple.com/us/app/remote-rowing-coach/id1507591443

snippet.title: Medium Intensity Rowing Training Session (6 x 5 minutes, 2 minutes rest)
snippet.description:
In this medium intensity training session, I discuss adjusting your center of gravity to be better prepared to work with the rowing machine. 

The protocol for the training session is:

6 x 5 minutes at rate 24spm, with 2 minutes of passive rest between each interval. 

The app featured in this video is currently in beta testing and my clients are using it to facilitate programming and data transfer their training plans. snippet.description:
All of my Preset ErgZone rowing training plans are available here: https://www.erg.zone/discover?source=coach-bergenroth

In this video I discuss the three levels of training plans that I have available on the ErgZone platform. 

I have created a rowing training plan curriculum, that provides a structure for you to progress through from beginning rowing and learning the correct technique to intermediate rowing training plans for your first 2k or 5k erg test, to more advanced plans for those competing at competitions at any level. 

I have pored my 37 years of experience into these plans. So for athletes and fitness enthusiasts on a budget, you can get top quality programming to help you towards your vision and goals for your fitness and rowing.

snippet.title: Video: 1b a. The Coach Bergenroth Rowing App - Rowing Training Session Programming and Auto Uploads
snippet.description:
In this video, I demonstrate the updated features of my Rowing Training App - Coach Bergenroth used by my clients enrolled in my individualized training plans. 

I am always looking for opportunities to innovate the technology that supports my athletes and clients.

I have been working hard to automate programming of the Concept2 PM5 monitor with the chosen training session.

When a training session has been configured, it is now possible to press a START TRAINING button on the training plan screen of the app, which will initiate a flow that will allow pairing the device to a Concept2 PM5 rowing machine monitor. 

The app will then program the monitor with the correct intervals. On completion of the training session, the app will automatically upload the training data to my training management system. 

As a result, there are more detailed statistics for each interval available than typical on other systems. This allows me to dial into the data at a deeper level and discover more training insights to help.

snippet.title: Erg Dude 2 - Galactic RowDown - Video Game For The Concept2
snippet.description:
Download Erg Dude 2 for iOS devices here üëâ https://apps.apple.com/za/app/erg-dude-2-galactic-rowdown/id6504142557

Blast off into fitness with Erg Dude 2! Burn calories, and challenge yourself with the ultimate Concept2 rowing app. Download now for an out-of-this-world workout!

Blast Off Into Fitness with Erg Dude 2: Galactic RowDown!

Are you ready to take your rowing workouts to another galaxy? Erg Dude 2: Galactic RowDown is the ultimate Concept2 rowing app that combines the thrill of space adventures with the intensity of rowing. Whether you're a seasoned rower or just starting, this immersive app will make every stroke count!

Join Erg Dude on an Epic Adventure In Erg Dude 2, you'll play as Erg Dude, a fearless space explorer shot down by the evil Nexar Voidstalker. To get back home, you must row through five out-of-this-world levels, each packed with challenges, surprises, and heart-pounding action. From dodging alien asteroids to hurling sonic grenades, this app turns your workouts into a cosmic journey!

Key Features:

Immersive Gameplay: Experience the excitement of battling enemies in space while simultaneously working out. Erg Dude 2 merges engaging gameplay with effective fitness training, making it the most enjoyable way to burn calories and build endurance.

Story Mode: Track your progress as the story unfolds, with each level designed to enhance different aspects of your rowing technique and overall performance. Watch as you grow stronger and more skilled with every session.

Power-Ups and Upgrades: Collect power-ups like shields and sonic grenades to boost your abilities and overcome even the toughest challenges. These enhancements will keep you motivated as you push through each level.

Leaderboards: Compete against friends, teammates, and players worldwide. Achieve the highest scores and rise to the top of the leaderboard, proving you're the best in the galaxy!

Tailored Workouts for All Levels: Whether you're a competitive rower or new to the sport, Erg Dude 2 offers a range of difficulty levels and workout intensities. Customize your training sessions to match your fitness goals, from endurance building to high-intensity intervals.

Dynamic Challenges: Each level presents unique obstacles and enemies, ensuring that no two workouts are the same. Erg Dude 2 keeps your training sessions fresh and exciting, making it easier to stay committed to your fitness journey.

Galactic Boss Battles: Face off against Nexar Voidstalker in epic boss battles that test your strength, endurance, and rowing skills. Can you defeat him and make it back home?

Free Trial Available: Not sure if Erg Dude 2 is right for you? Try our FREE version! Enjoy a 2-3 minute introduction to the app, giving you a taste of the adventure and a chance to test your skills. With access to 20% of the game, you can see if Erg Dude 2 is the perfect fit for your fitness routine before committing to the full version.

Upgrade to the Full Experience: Unlock the entire Erg Dude 2: Galactic RowDown experience with our Premium version. Gain access to longer sessions, burn more calories, and increase your chances of dominating the leaderboard. With up to 30-40 minutes of exercise per session, it's the perfect way to stay in shape while having fun!

Why Choose Erg Dude 2? Erg Dude 2 isn't just a rowing app‚Äîit's a full-blown adventure that makes fitness fun and effective. By turning your workout into a game, you'll find yourself more motivated to push through tough sessions and reach your fitness goals. Plus, the integration with the Concept2 rowing machine ensures you're getting a high-quality workout every time.

Ready to Row Your Way to Fitness and Fun? Download Erg Dude 2: Galactic RowDown today and embark on the ultimate rowing adventure! Whether you're aiming to improve your rowing technique, increase your endurance, or just have a blast while working out, Erg Dude 2 has you covered. So strap in, grab your Concept2, and get ready for an unforgettable journey through the cosmos!

snippet.description:

snippet.title: 3x9 Minute Rowing Workout: Aerobic Base, Control, Recovery & Stroke Technique
snippet.description:
Working on your aerobic base is always the foundation of good performance on the rowing machine. 

I begin with a 5 minute pick drill so that you warm up appropriately before the main training session. 

This is a low-intensity session, aiming for around 70% of maximum heart rate.

The session is 3 x 9 minutes with 1:30 rest between intervals. I will take you through this training session, discussing the following points:

1) Always row with control and precision.   
2) float on the slide, relaxing during recovery, especially during the last part.
3) Good recovery mechanics are essential for a well-executed drive.
4) How to row an effective stroke to make your force curve a haystack.
5) Drop the rate if you need to stay within your heart rate zone, but don't sacrifice force application and form.

snippet.localized.title: 3x9 Minute Rowing Workout: Aerobic Base, Control, Recovery & Stroke Technique
snippet.localized.description:
Working on your aerobic base is always the foundation of good performance on the rowing machine. 

I begin with a 5 minute pick drill so that you warm up appropriately before the main training session. 

This is a low-intensity session, aiming for around 70% of maximum heart rate.

The session is 3 x 9 minutes with 1:30 rest between intervals. I will take you through this training session, discussing the following points:

1) Always row with control and precision.   
2) float on the slide, relaxing during recovery, especially during the last part.
3) Good recovery mechanics are essential for a well-executed drive.
4) How to row an effective stroke to make your force curve a haystack.
5) Drop the rate if you need to stay within your heart rate zone, but don't sacrifice force application and form.

snippet.title: Coach Bergenroth App - Beta : Video Analysis Recording Feature
snippet.description:
This is an update for beta-testers of my in-development rowing coaching app. 

Full blog here: https://www.coachbergenroth.com/rowing-video-analysis-enhanced-in-app-video-capture-feature/

I‚Äôve been eager to develop this functionality for some time. The primary aim is to enhance rowing video analysis with real-time force application feedback. By integrating force curve data directly onto recorded footage, users can view their technique in slow motion alongside crucial performance metrics, enabling detailed analysis of both technique and force application.

Previously in my workflow, video review and force curve analysis were separate processes. This latest update in the Coach Bergenroth app‚Äôs beta version revolutionizes this approach. Now, coaches and athletes can record their technique and simultaneously view metrics such as elapsed time, power, and drive length, with the force curve data superimposed on the video.

To use this feature, simply connect the app to a Concept2 Ergometer‚Äôs PM5 using the standard procedure. A camera icon is positioned in the top right of the metrics view. Tap this icon, position your device so your profile is in the camera‚Äôs view, and press the record button on the top left of the screen. If prompted, allow the app to record your screen.

During your training session, the app captures everything displayed on the screen. A green ‚Äúrecording‚Äù indicator confirms that the process is active. After completing your session, press the stop icon next to the recording button to end the capture.

A preview window will pop up, allowing you to save the recorded session to your device‚Äôs photos. This feature captures all 17 metrics, facilitating simultaneous data collection and video analysis.

For a glimpse of what this feature can do, check out the example rowing video analysis above. Enjoy exploring this new addition to your training toolkit!

snippet.title: Mastering the 5K Row: My Expert Strategies for Optimal Performance - Version 2.0 (edited)
snippet.description:
The original version was missing the graphics relevant to making pushes in your plan. This version restores those graphics. 

Hi everyone, welcome to my latest video, where I share my in-depth insights on creating the perfect race plan for a 5K row. If you're joining us for the first time or a loyal subscriber, I'm thrilled to have you here. Please like, share, and subscribe for more content like this!

In this comprehensive guide, I cover:

1. The Art of Pacing: I explain how to manage your pace effectively throughout a 5K row, emphasizing the balance between speed and endurance. I discuss the relationship between your 2K and 5K times and how to adjust your pace for the best results.

2. Mindset and Strategy: I delve into the mental and strategic aspects crucial for rowing a 5K. I talk about the importance of staying focused on the present and not getting overwhelmed by the distance ahead.

3. Technique and Rhythm: Discover my tips for maintaining a strong, consistent rhythm throughout the race. I emphasize the importance of stroke length, acceleration, and efficient energy use.

4. Endurance and Power: Learn how to handle fatigue and maintain power in the final stages of the race. I offer practical advice on managing both the physical and mental challenges as you near the finish line.

5. Training and Improvement: Whether you aim to beat your best or complete your first 5K row, my advice is tailored to help you achieve your goals.

I'd love to hear about your experiences with 5K rowing in the comments below. For personalized coaching, visit my website at https://www.coachbergenroth.com for a free consultation. I have helped hundreds of athletes improve their 5K times, and I'm here to help you, too!

If you found this video valuable, please like it, share it with others and subscribe for more content designed to help you improve your rowing speed and technique.

snippet.title: My Latest  Rowing App Invention - Video Analysis With Force Curve Overlay.
snippet.description:
My latest prototype invention.  Video analysis filmed in app with the metrics and force curve overlay.

I‚Äôve been wanted to try to build this as a feature into one of my apps for a while. 

I got a few hours yesterday afternoon and managed to come up with this.

It would be better if the force curve was truly real-time, so that the video could be slowed down and you could directly see biomechanics and the effect on the force curve.

I like the fact that you can see stroke length in the video as well.  Might be helpful to pinpoint technical issues.  I don‚Äôt know.  I‚Äôm just tinkering really. 

I could probably invent a lot of really cool stuff, if I didn‚Äôt have so much grading to do, but life is full of choices. 

Let me know what you think in the comments. 

#innovation #rowing #indoorrowing #appdeveloper #concept2 #rowingcoach

snippet.title: Effective Rowing Technique On The Drive: Join Coach Neil Bergenroth for a Technical Row-Along
snippet.description:
Warm Up

Reverse Pick drill for 4 minutes.
Row steady at 20 - 24 spm 4 minutes
2-minute water break and stretch

Work

1 minute of drills, 2 minutes of rowing [
Tap Drill x 2 (6 minutes) - body prep
Top 1/2 of Drive x 2 (6 minutes) - body prep
Legs, back, no arm break x 2 (6 minutes) - body prep
Acceleration drill (6 minutes) - slide control

] - 24 minutes

5 - minute steady state 20 spm to 24 spm

snippet.title: Hour of Power - Biomechanics with Damien O'Meara from NSWIS
snippet.description:
As part of the National Virtual Development Series, Rowing NSW hosted its first Hour of Power for 2025 on 12 February. 

We were joined by Damien O'Meara, Senior Biomechanist at the NSW Institute of Sport, who gave some amazing insights into:

- Biomechanics tech & analysis

- The new "Boat Run" metric focusing in on how the boat runs, so the aim is to highlight the attributes a rower needs to be fast on water, as opposed to power and endurance which shows up in off-water performance, e.g. ergo results.

snippet.title: Hour of Power 2024 - S&C with Kellyanne Redman from NSWIS
snippet.description:
As part of the National Virtual Development Series, Rowing NSW hosted its first Hour of Power for 2024 on Thursday 11 July. 

We were joined by Kellyanne Redman PhD, Strength and Conditioning coach at the NSW Institute of Sport, who gave some amazing insights into:

- Essential S&C exercises and routines, preparing for the Pathway
- Injury prevention strategies
- Balancing intensity and recovery

Check out past Hours of Power on the Rowing NSW website at this link: https://www.rowingnsw.asn.au/competition/hour-of-power

snippet.title: Japan Part 2 with Matt, Jordan and Jonte
snippet.description:
Matt, Jordan, and Jonte travel to Ishikawa with the Toyota Boshoku rowing team. They are in for a hard training camp to find some extra speed after a narrow defeat from their arch rival, company NTT. The guys experience a bit of culture shock living in a truly rural Japanese style, from eating strange foods to sleeping on the floor and using public services. 

Video: Matt Dunham

snippet.title: Maadi Regatta reflections of elite rowers
snippet.description:
For many school rowers, the Maadi Regatta sometimes feels like the Olympics. Two thousand rowers from more than 150 schools competing for a spot in a heat, semi-final, repechage and if you‚Äôre lucky, an A Final. Watching the action this year, some current and past top New Zealand rowers. RowingHub‚Äôs Wendy Petrie caught up with them to discover that immediate success did not start at school, but the Maadi Regatta did instil a love of the sport. 

Video Producer: Wendy Petrie 
Video Production: Joe Harcourt

snippet.title: Jordan Parry tries coastal
snippet.description:
Olympian Jordan Parry (AKA Paz) jumped into a coastal boat for the first time and coastal rower Matt Dunham was there to get his thoughts. It wasn't exactly smooth sailing from Paz's point of view - the timing thing threw him off, and he said his sprint game needs some work. But he's already planning to give it another go thanks to Matt's enthusiasm.

Video: Matt Dunham

snippet.title: From Car Park to Champion: Bobbie‚Äôs Incredible Rowing Journey üö£‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è‚ú®
snippet.description:
During the Maadi Regatta at Lake KarƒÅpiro, Olympic rowing champion Michael Brake (as part of his Milford Maadi Moments Challenge Series) went head-to-head with Year 10 student Bobbie Wilson from Sacred Heart Girls' College Hamilton in a spontaneous sprint race... in the car park! üí®

Bobbie left the Olympic champ in the dust‚Äîearning herself a pair of socks, a new fan, and a whole lot of respect.

Impressed by her raw speed and talent, Michael reached out to the school‚Äôs Rowing Manager. That moment kickstarted something incredible. Bobbie was soon invited to cox at the NZ Beach Sprint Championships at Orewa Beach, racing alongside New Zealand‚Äôs elite‚Äîincluding Olympic gold medalist Emma Twigg.

And it didn‚Äôt stop there. When Emma couldn‚Äôt cox, Bobbie stepped up to lead the King‚Äôs College U17 coxed quad sculls team‚Äîbringing home gold! ü•á

Then came a surprise twist: Mike and Bobbie discovered they both whakapapa to NgƒÅti Porou and are actually distant cousins! üß¨üí´

From a car park race to national medals and unexpected family ties‚Äîthis is a story of speed, spirit, and serendipity.

snippet.title: The 2025 Maadi Regatta U 18 Boys' Coxed Eight A Final - Maadi Cup race
snippet.description:
The boys' Maadi Cup final was electric, with Westlake Boys High School seeking the elusive boys under 18 sweep trifecta. After a false start, the race restarted, and Westlake surged to an early lead. St Bede‚Äôs briefly took control, but Westlake responded at the 1250m mark, surging ahead to win in 6:07.48. St Bede‚Äôs finished second (6:10.23), with Christ‚Äôs College taking bronze (6:14.22).

Westlake Boys High School Coach Andy Hay was elated:

‚ÄúI‚Äôm stunned. These boys have put in unbelievable work. I‚Äôve never met a more focused group. They truly deserve this.‚Äù

Video production: Joe Harcourt 
With livestream footage from Altitude HD

snippet.title: 2025 Maadi Regatta - Girls Coxed Eight A Final - the Levin 75th Jubilee Cup
snippet.description:
St Margaret‚Äôs College claimed the Levin 75th Jubilee Cup for the eighth time, executing a dominant wire-to-wire victory at the 2025 Maadi Regatta. 

‚ÄúWe changed the entire seating order after a bad heat, and it just worked,‚Äù said cox Bella Harris. ‚ÄúI told the girls we needed to make this our legacy. We hadn‚Äôt won in seven years, so we had to do it for everyone before us.‚Äù

Waikato Dio took silver with Rangi Ruru Girls School earning bronze.

Video Production: Joe Harcourt 
With livestream footage thanks to Altitude HD.

snippet.title: New World Record
snippet.description:
Finn Hamill, world champion in the coastal men's solo, and Matt Dunham, 2023 mixed double beach sprint champion, successfully completed a gruelling, 45km journey around Hong Kong Island. Their impressive performance earned them a course record, finishing in 3 hours, 23 minutes, and 40 seconds - a full 9 minutes ahead of the previous record. In a special
episode of Community Chat, Matt shares their adventure with us. 

Video production: Matt Dunham

snippet.title: Who‚Äôs in charge?
snippet.description:
Olympians Emma Twigg and Tom Mackintosh put each other in their place with some goodhearted banter at Boston‚Äôs Head of the Charles. From Paris to Boston, Olympic double medallist Emma Twigg is no stranger to the iconic Head of the Charles Regatta, having competed in it a dozen times. This year, she‚Äôs enlisted fellow Olympian and teammate Tom Mackintosh (AKA T-Mack), to help her prepare for her race. Watch Twiggy prepare for her single scull race at the hallowed Cambridge Boat Club, with Tom in tow.

Video Producer: Wendy Petrie
Video Production: Picture Show Ltd

snippet.title: Saltwater Creek

That‚Äôs a lot of rowing traffic for a narrow piece of water barely 1km long. Andy Hay went to see how they turn out the champions in one of the South Island‚Äôs ‚Äúbest-kept secrets‚Äù.

snippet.title: Avondale Intermediate students take to the Whau River
snippet.description:
Snaking off the Waitemata Harbour, is the Whau River running quietly beside the busy Auckland suburbs of Avondale and Henderson. Yet for many locals it‚Äôs a place they have never visited. West End Rowing Club together with partners is piloting a programme for school children to experience the river. RowingHub‚Äôs Wendy Petrie went along to see students of Avondale Intermediate making the absolute best of a great opportunity, coastal rowing, kayaking and bush walking.

Video Producer: Wendy Petrie 
Video Production: Picture Show Ltd

snippet.title: Wolfgangsee part 1 scenery for indoor rowing - Lake Wolfgang, Austria - rowing machine
snippet.description:
What a view! ...follow along and let's cross Lake Wolfgang from West to East. In the background, the 10 o'clock church bells gently mark our start in Sankt Gilgen. Heading East to Strobl, passing Sankt Wolfgang we'll see the snowy Schafberg mountain and many more. (reupload in higher image quality)

Distance: 13 km

Obviously we had chosen the wrong boat type for the conditions present in the beginning ;-) but in the end it turned out to be a very enjoyable rowing trip.

As usual, some parts are muted or with music overlay to protect privacy rights of people involved.

snippet.title: (21.05) 30 min rowing machine interval session - flying high at high SPMs
snippet.description:
another quick but effective early morning pre-work session? Here we go, during the first 5 minutes we get our body warmed up, then we'll have a 1 min on / 1 min off ladder up to 36 strokes per minute. Then a 3 minute recovery phase to be prepared for a 5 minute medium/high intensity section at around 28 SPMs. For the final 6 minutes we will cool down and relax...

snippet.title: (21.04) - 10k boat race 70 min WATER FUN - rowing machine workout -  virtual on board view
snippet.description:
Become a member and help us grow - access exlusive workouts and scenery
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC9wc-BmsZJeNMpy5LkaixBA/join

In this video, you'll follow along on board a mixed masters 2x boat.

This video will be quite interesting for those of you who usually
do erg only. Be it at home, at the crossfit box or at your favorite
gym as it will cover a whole rowing event.

Rowing the boat to the start line, the umpire boat and signals,
the usual trouble when many different boat classes start at the
same place, navigation around the turnaround buoys, crosswinds,
headwinds, not so perfect rowing conditions and so on...

Boat: Schellenbacher

snippet.title: (21.02) - the time trial - 40 minutes rowing machine workout
snippet.description:
If you like what we are doing and want to help us create more interesting content consider becoming a channel member - starting from only 2,99 EUR - CLICK- https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC9wc-BmsZJeNMpy5LkaixBA/join

this is gonna be tough at the end

preparing intervals for extensive warmup followed by a 4 minute time trail. give all you've got - your peak performance


This video is suitable for any rowing machine, as it is a timed workout. In the video, you'll find an target intensity column. If you are an experienced rower, you might work with intensity based on your 2k time. If you are a beginner, watching your heart rate is a good way of monitoring the overall stress put on your body during a workout, in this case use the percentage column as heart rate zone target. I.e. the blue 60 - 70 % indicator suggest you to row in the 60-70% range of your (estimated or tested) maximum heart rate. A heart rate monitor is highly recomended. In the past chest straps were the only way to reliably measure HR. Recently a few products came to market which would work on your arm too (i.e. Polar OH1)

The SPM box shows a target stroke per minute range. Keep in mind to watch your form and correct sequence even at higher stroke rates. Use the low SPM ranges to closely look at what you are doing through the full sequence.

#rowingmachine #workout

snippet.title: Q&A with Cleary & Marshy
snippet.description:
Australian team rower Sam Marsh and Olympian Jack Cleary join Rowing WA for an in-depth chat to create the Act Belong Commit Healthway Video (filmed in 2022).

Sam and Jack as Act Belong Commit Ambassadors opened up about the challenges both physical and mental that they go through on a daily basis as elite athletes.

Good mental health is much more than not having a mental illness; it is about mental wellness. We know that staying active connecting with others and doing something meaningful are powerfully protective of mental health and provide the foundations for mental wellbeing.

Thank you to Sam and Jack for their time and for sharing their stories with us.

Thank you also to Healthway WA and Act Belong Commit for their support of this video. 

Healthway: https://www.healthway.wa.gov.au/
Act Belong Commit: https://www.actbelongcommit.org.au/

snippet.title: Guaranteed ways to Level Up as a Coxswain (with Hayley Verbunt)

Hayley Verbunt is the coxswain of the 2023 Australian Women's Eight & has made her way to that seat by going through the ranks of her club crews and then the Aussie pathway system!

snippet.title: The Resilient Rower
snippet.description:
Hour of Power #3 2023

The Resilient Rower - How to Prevent and Manage Rowing Injuries

Greg Kerr from Horizon Physiotherapy hosted the third Hour of Power of the year - a fantastic presentation called 'The Resilient Rower'. Greg is a highly experienced rower and physiotherapist, and is the clinical director at Horizon. The workshop drew around 30 participants and covered common rowing injuries, how to avoid them in the first place, how to manage them once they've appeared, and how to optimise training and technique to stay healthy and pain-free. Among other things, we learned about why Greg likes to see 'fishing rod' posture in rowers, why we should be paying way more attention to the Thoraco Lumbar Fascia, and why the 'Kerr Squat' should be considered as a part of everyone's warmup routine. Huge thanks to Greg for sharing his time and expertise with us. 

Read more about Greg's work at https://www.horizonphysio.com.au/the-team/greg-kerr

Read more about Greg's work at https://www.horizonphysio.com.au/the-team/greg-kerr

snippet.title: Regulate, Ready, Recover: Athlete Preparation for Rowers
snippet.description:
Hour of Power #1 2023

Presenter - Dr. Sacha Fulton from Peak Preparation

Designed to help coaches & athletes see the big picture requirements of athlete preparation and how all the pieces of the puzzle fit together. It is our hope that the session serves as a reminder to coaches that building a high performance athlete is merely an added bonus but creating a healthy, robust, confident, engaged and supported member of society should always be the goal. In this session we will explore how the concept of ‚Äòregulate, ready, recover‚Äô can be applied in each individual training session as well as across an entire season for both coach and athlete.

snippet.title: Physiology of Rowing
snippet.description:
Rowing WA Hour of Power presentation from 2017

Presenter - Martyn Binnie (WAIS Sport Scientist)

Are you a coach confused by why some athletes respond to training loads better than others? Are you an athlete trying to achieve success but you can't complete the training program properly? Come along to this session to find all of this out and more. Managing training loads and understanding how each athlete responds differently to stimulus is a fundamental aspect of rowing.

Slides available at https://www.rowingwa.asn.au/scripts/download/file/&id=2acu5jwiccwinmgz

snippet.title: Reflections from the Science of Rowing podcast üéôÔ∏è
snippet.description:
Reflections from the Science of Rowing podcast üéôÔ∏è: Diving deep into the challenges of longitudinal data collection with Nicole, Lisa, and Joe. üìäüîç

It's all about understanding the noise in the data‚Äîhow one standout test day or an off-day can skew perceptions of performance trends. Instead of relying on snapshots, tracking weekly data revealed the bigger picture: those peaks and troughs tell a story, but the real insight lies in the upward trend over time. üöÄ

From testing to monitoring, it‚Äôs a shift in mindset for sustainable performance growth. üí°üí™ #ScienceOfRowing #DataDrivenTraining #RowingInsights

snippet.title: ü§ñ The future of training and AI?
snippet.description:
ü§ñ The future of training and AI? It‚Äôs all about optimization‚Äîbut with a human touch. In the next 5-10 years, we see AI tools like the @athletica.ai avatar becoming indispensable assistant coaches, analyzing data and giving insights while leaving the context and people skills to the real coaches. üß†

üéì As educators and practitioners, we‚Äôre committed to guiding this evolution, ensuring technology empowers coaches to deliver smarter, more effective training sessions‚Äîbalancing cutting-edge AI with the art of coaching.

üöÄ In partnership with @hiitscience and @athletica, we‚Äôre bringing these science-driven strategies to rowers everywhere.

snippet.description:

In this month‚Äôs Science of Rowing, Lisa dives into a fascinating study exploring the role of nutrition in rib stress injuries.

Key findings include:
‚úÖ The importance of adequate calorie intake to support training.
‚úÖ Tracking menstrual cycles for early detection of changes in bone health (for females).
‚úÖ Using rib-specific bone density scans as a breakthrough tool to detect and prevent injuries.

snippet.title: Low Back Pain and Rowing Biomechanics with Frank Nugent
snippet.description:
Alex interviews Frank Nugent who was the lead author of the article review - The relationship between rowing-related low back pain and rowing biomechanics: a systematic review. Frank is a former rower, rowing coach, strength and conditioning coach, and an assistant lecturer at the University of Limerick.

Frank describes what a systematic review is, the key findings from the research, including the wider body of work around the 2021 consensus statement for preventing and managing low back pain (link below to the article and the plain language summaries).  Frank also describes how this has informed his coaching practice while also providing real world examples.

https://bjsm.bmj.com/content/55/16/893.abstract

Hi, I‚Äôm Xeno M√ºller‚ÄîOlympic gold and silver medalist in the men‚Äôs single scull and an elite rowing coach for high school athletes. Today, I want to talk to parents who are new to rowing‚Äîespecially if your child is considering joining a junior rowing program this fall.

Here‚Äôs what most parents don‚Äôt realize: the learning curve in rowing is steep. And when your child is one of 30 kids at tryouts, knowing how to handle the rowing machine, how to pace, how to row with proper form‚Äîthat matters. Bad technique creates injuries and slow progress. My coaching prevents that.

I teach kids how to hold the handle to avoid blisters, how to condition their bodies before rowing starts, how to visualize the stroke, and how to self-correct. This isn‚Äôt just about being fit‚Äîit‚Äôs about being ready.

When your child shows up at tryouts already rowing efficiently, it‚Äôs like walking into class already knowing the answers. Coaches notice. Your child‚Äôs confidence soars. And you‚Äîthe parent‚Äîknow you gave them the best possible start.

If you want your beginner high school rower to be prepared this fall, let‚Äôs talk. Go to eliterowingcoach.com or book a call with me. Let‚Äôs make rowing a sport your child thrives in.

snippet.description:
I talk about the paradox in junior rowing where rowers can train hard on the erg all winter but still not win seat races. This is because poor erg technique can ruin boat moving skills. I share my approach to coaching that focuses on transferring efficient erg technique to the boat, using the legs, core, and handle together to move the boat with maximum efficiency. I also discuss how poor technical habits, whether on the erg or in the boat, can limit performance gains even for schools that row year-round. As an Olympic gold and silver medalist, I coach high school athletes worldwide on how to stop spinning their wheels and start moving boats faster.

snippet.title: Junior Athlete Ever Changing Body
snippet.description:
Why Every Rowing Coach (And Every Coach) Needs to Understand This: Teenagers Are Changing Faster Than We Think

By Xeno M√ºller | Olympic Gold & Silver Medalist | Elite Rowing Coach

Let‚Äôs say it plainly: kids change‚Äîand they change fast.

As obvious as that sounds, you‚Äôd be surprised how often it‚Äôs overlooked in sports coaching. Especially in junior athletes, where the goal is long-term development, not short-term dominance.

A Rowing Coach‚Äôs Reality: The Athlete Today Is Not the Same as Yesterday
As a rowing coach‚Äîand this applies across tennis, swimming, gymnastics, and every sport that involves grace, timing, and physical progression‚ÄîI've witnessed firsthand how puberty isn't just physical growth. It‚Äôs a recalibration of the entire system: bones, muscles, tendons, brain chemistry, psychology, and even diet.

One day your rower seems powerful and balanced. The next, their timing is off, their patience is low, and they‚Äôre frustrated. This isn‚Äôt regression. It‚Äôs growth in disguise.

The Hidden Tug-of-War: Bones, Muscles, Tendons, Brain
When young athletes grow, they go through a biomechanical balancing act:

Bones lengthen.
Tendons and muscles struggle to catch up.
Flexibility changes.
Neuromuscular pathways need to be re-learned.
Their body isn‚Äôt betraying them. It‚Äôs reorganizing itself. Coaches who don‚Äôt recognize this mistake temporary misalignment for lack of effort or discipline.

And here‚Äôs the deeper layer: the brain has to remap movement patterns.

That‚Äôs why something that ‚Äúclicked‚Äù last week suddenly feels clumsy. It‚Äôs not mental laziness‚Äîit‚Äôs neurological recalibration. As a coach, you either adapt to this... or you burn out your athletes.

The Iron Truth for Girls, and the Risk of Overload for Boys
Female athletes often face dietary deficiencies during key growth years‚Äîiron being one of the most common. Without proper iron levels, oxygen delivery drops, fatigue increases, and performance suffers.

This isn‚Äôt fixed with a motivational speech‚Äîit‚Äôs fixed with awareness, communication, and action.

Meanwhile, boys often mask insecurity in the gym. They chase numbers on the squat rack, deadlift beyond their limits, and forget that technique and patience build lifelong athletes‚Äînot ego lifts.

Both situations can lead to injuries, and worse, a loss of love for the sport.

What Every Rowing Coach‚Äîand Every Coach‚ÄîMust Do
Listen first.
Adapt every day.
Accept non-linear progress.
Fuel smartly.
Talk about physiology openly.
Empower with education.
We coaches are not just timekeepers or drill masters. We are interpreters of change, guides through adolescence, and advocates for health over hype.

As a rowing coach, I don‚Äôt just analyze split times‚ÄîI observe body mechanics, emotional tone, energy, focus, and patterns of change. That‚Äôs how I help rowers win seat races, improve erg scores, and‚Äîmost importantly‚Äîstay in love with the process.

Your Athlete is Not a Machine. They‚Äôre a Miracle in Progress.
To every parent reading this: give your child grace.

To every athlete: be patient with your body and brain.

To every coach: pay attention, and keep learning.

In my own Olympic journey, I saw that the best performances came not from brute force, but from learning how to listen‚Äîto my body, my coach, and the feedback that mattered most.

Change is not the enemy. Unacknowledged change is.

Let‚Äôs coach for growth, not just results.





www.elite-rowing-coach.com

snippet.title: Rowers! Upper Respiratory Infections (URIs) are often mismanaged.
snippet.description:
Upper Respiratory Illness in Rowing: What Coaches and Athletes Need to Know

As a former Olympic rower and now an elite rowing coach, I want to share my personal experience and a call for awareness around a persistent and overlooked issue in the rowing world: upper respiratory infections (URIs) and the way we respond to them as athletes and coaches.

Athlete Mentality vs. Medical Reality

Rowers are trained‚Äîalmost indoctrinated‚Äîto be tough. Push through pain. Show up no matter what. We‚Äôre told that unless we‚Äôre running a fever or bedridden, we train. That mentality can get you far in competition, but it can also take you straight into a doctor‚Äôs office‚Ä¶ with a wheeze.

I‚Äôve been there.

During my competitive years, I remember developing an upper respiratory infection. I did what many rowers do instinctively: blew my nose hard, tried to cough my way to clear lungs, and refused to miss training. But here‚Äôs what happened instead:
 ‚Ä¢ Sinus infection from blowing too hard
 ‚Ä¢ Secondary pulmonary infection from prolonged coughing
 ‚Ä¢ Antibiotics prescribed
 ‚Ä¢ Wheezing severe enough that I was given a bronchodilator (which, by the way, is only permitted out of competition)

The medical advice I received early on lacked crucial context. It didn‚Äôt include cautions about rest, recovery timing, or the risks of pushing through a URI. It wasn‚Äôt until I trained under one of my Olympic coaches that the guidance changed.

What My Olympic Coach Taught Me

He had seen it too many times. His response was swift: ‚ÄúStart antibiotics immediately.‚Äù
Why? Because, in his experience, the longer we wait, the more likely the illness morphs into a deeper infection. Athletes often cough themselves into worsening conditions‚Äîbronchitis, pneumonia‚Äîwhen early rest and targeted treatment might have prevented that entirely.

His philosophy was shaped by years of observing rowers lose weeks of training (and even entire racing seasons) because they didn‚Äôt pull back soon enough.

What I See Now as a Coach

Today, I work with high school rowers and club athletes. And I see the exact same pattern.
 ‚Ä¢ Clubs tell kids to train unless they have a fever.
 ‚Ä¢ Winter training is often indoors, with poor ventilation.
 ‚Ä¢ Athletes are lined up on ergs, sweating and breathing heavily‚Äîwhile others are coughing, sniffling, and clearly sick.
 ‚Ä¢ One sick athlete becomes five. Five become ten.

What‚Äôs worse is that the culture still rewards showing up sick. The ‚Äútough-it-out‚Äù mentality is celebrated while coaches fail to recognize the long-term consequences‚Äîboth to the individual and the entire team.

Post-COVID Immunity Gap?

Here‚Äôs a theory I‚Äôve been tossing around (as a coach, not a doctor):
During the COVID lockdowns, we had less exposure to common viruses. Kids weren‚Äôt swapping germs like usual, and for a few years, we saw very little illness. Now, with everyone back in close quarters, we‚Äôre seeing more severe URIs than before. It could be an immunity lag. It could be bad luck. But one thing is for sure:

Coughing too hard, blowing too hard, and training through upper respiratory issues is not a sign of grit. It‚Äôs a recipe for long-term damage.

What Coaches Need to Do
 1. Stop glorifying the ‚Äújust show up‚Äù mindset. If your athlete is coughing, wheezing, or visibly struggling to breathe, they should not be erging next to healthy teammates.
 2. Educate your rowers‚Äîespecially the young ones‚Äîon how to recover properly. Rest isn‚Äôt laziness. It‚Äôs recovery.
 3. Create clear protocols for sick athletes. ‚ÄúNo fever = show up‚Äù is not enough.
 4. Separate the sick from the healthy in indoor training settings, especially during cold and flu season.
 5. Recognize that training through illness weakens the team. You might feel like you‚Äôre helping them build toughness, but in reality, you‚Äôre trading short-term appearances for long-term resilience.

‚∏ª

This message is for every coach and every rower who has tried to ‚Äúrow through‚Äù a cold.

Let your lungs heal. Let your team stay healthy.
Being tough is about knowing when to stop just as much as it is about knowing when to push.

If this resonates with your experience‚Äîor if you‚Äôve seen these patterns in your own club or team‚ÄîI‚Äôd love to hear your story. The more we bring this issue to light, the faster we can change the culture around training and recovery in rowing.

‚Äì Xeno

snippet.title: College Rowers Win Your Seat Races #rowingcamp
snippet.description:
Reach out to me to get faster!


Most people see this as a piece of an old oar. I see a scalpel, a precision tool. If you're rowing in college right now, congratulations, you made it through the recruiting gauntlet. Your erg score got you in. But guess what? That erg score won't move you from the 4V to the 3V or from the 2V to the 1V. Seat racing will, and seat racing is all about one thing: blade work. How you place it, how you extract it, how clean you are, how you blend into the rhythm without disrupting it and still add speed. That's where that scalpel comes in. I've trained with the best coaches in the world. I've won Olympic gold and silver in the single scull. My final 500-meter sprint is still the fastest ever recorded, 1:36.56. snippet.title: Why Missing Out on a Rowing Camp May Be the Best Thing for Your Rower #rowingcamp #rowingcoach
snippet.description:
Reach out to me to get faster in rowing. 


The truth about erg speed versus boat speed, and why it matters, especially for recruiting. I'm XENO Olympic gold and silver medalist in the single scull, recruited to Brown University as the top US prospect and the most trusted online rowing coach for high school athletes who want to get recruited. Let me explain a big, big misunderstanding in rowing. A fast erg doesn't mean you move the boat fast. I've seen it again and again, athletes who destroy the erg, but don't win their seat races. And why is that? Well, because the rowing machine forgives bad technique. You can yank the handle, the flywheel will spin. But in the boat, speed only comes if the blade enters and exits the water at the right time. That's where many rowers fall apart. Now, here's something parents rarely hear. Lighter rowers with the same flaws as heavier rowers will move a boat faster, simply because they disturb the water less. Bigger athletes with technical flaws do more damage to boat speed, but recruiters don't see boat-moving ability. They see erg scores. And that's why I coach both. I teach Olympic-level efficiency that works on the erg and translates into the boat. Because the right stroke is the same stroke. It's the timing, the rhythm, the connection, and I've mastered how to teach that. No rowing camp, no rowing camp does this consistently. Camps don't have the time or the depth of knowledge to correct what truly matters. I was trained by the best. I've won at the highest level, set an Olympic record, and now, I help rowers win their seat races and get recruited. Win their seat races, get recruited. If your son or daughter has a high school junior, time is running out. Don't waste another month on the wrong approach. Work with me. Let's get faster, let's get recruited.

snippet.title: Olympic Gold Medalist‚Äôs Path To Meditation Through Rowing Movement
snippet.description:
Today, something truly remarkable happened.
I was running a rowing workout for a group of dedicated individuals in their 60s and 70s. I‚Äôm certainly the younger one in the bunch, but what we shared today transcended age‚Äîit was about presence, precision, and something I can only describe as flow.
We were using our water-resistance rowers, which already add a timeless quality to the experience with their soothing, rushing sound. As we began warming up, I guided the group through an intentionally technical sequence‚Äîfocusing on nasal breathing, on keeping the shoulders relaxed and hanging from the neck, and on narrating each stroke internally.
This kind of self-narration‚Äîdescribing to yourself what you are doing, why you are doing it, and how‚Äîis one of the greatest tools I know. It‚Äôs how I trained for the Olympics. It‚Äôs how I race. It‚Äôs how I win. And more importantly‚Äîit‚Äôs how I find joy in the movement, regardless of the stakes.
What happens when I combine this internal narration with nasal breathing is nothing short of a switch being flipped. Even if I woke up feeling sluggish or unmotivated, the moment I begin this process‚Äîthe breath, the sequence, the awareness‚ÄîI enter a flow state. The breathing acts like a cleanse. The technical focus sharpens the blade of movement. And then‚Äîeverything flows. Legs stretch the spine, the fingertips hang, the stroke becomes a reach, a glide, an elegant surge.
And then, the sound.
That‚Äôs when I told the group: ‚ÄúWhat you hear in the drum of your WaterRower‚Äîthat swoosh‚Äîthat‚Äôs the sound of something ancient. The sound of water being moved has been around since before we were. It‚Äôs the same sound you might‚Äôve heard from a little stream cutting through a valley a million years ago.‚Äù
It was one of those moments where time stops.
I went on, ‚ÄúThink about the sound of a crackling fire‚Ä¶ or a rock falling onto another rock. These are primal sounds. Ancient sounds. And we‚Äôre making one of them‚Äîby rowing. By accelerating water with our bodies. That‚Äôs poetry in motion.‚Äù
At that moment, we weren‚Äôt just exercising. We weren‚Äôt ‚Äògetting a workout in.‚Äô We were present. We were part of something bigger. We were escaping‚Äînot running away from anything‚Äîbut escaping into something: focus, rhythm, breath, movement.
It‚Äôs amazing what happens when you let your breath cleanse your thoughts. When your mind has space to wander and find patterns. When your focus doesn‚Äôt feel like a chore, but a release.
By the end of the session, I was energized‚Äînot just physically, but mentally. I was ready to make better decisions. To stay composed in a world that moves fast. And most importantly, to carry this sense of rhythm and presence into the rest of my day.
If you‚Äôve never experienced this kind of rowing, I encourage you‚Äîno matter your age‚Äîto try. It‚Äôs not just a workout. It‚Äôs a pathway to clarity. #rowing #coaching #meditation #innerpeace

snippet.title: Rowing Camp - Rowing - Perseverance
snippet.description:
www.elite-rowing-coach.com

Rowing Camp

The Power of Perseverance: A Rower‚Äôs Reflection


As I was walking home from Starbucks with my wife, I had an epiphany. We were talking about perseverance, happiness in work, and what it really means to develop as a person. My wife rowed in high school, so rowing is a familiar subject for her‚Äîlet alone the fact that she‚Äôs been married to me for nearly 30 years!

And in that moment, I felt this overwhelming need to commend those who dedicate themselves to the sport of rowing.

To the high school rowers who show up day in and day out, pushing themselves through fatigue, bad weather, and the never-ending pursuit of technical precision‚ÄîI see you.
To the college rowers who commit another four years to moving in perfect synchrony, even when they know not every boat will win‚ÄîI salute you.

What rowing does for character development is nothing short of extraordinary.

Rowing: A Sport Like No Other

Rowing is a physical sport. But it‚Äôs not just physical‚Äîit‚Äôs relentless.

Most sports demand endurance. But in rowing, every fiber of your body is engaged all at once. You don‚Äôt get breaks, you don‚Äôt get time to reset between plays‚Äîyou are always moving, always flowing, always striving for more.

Rowing teaches us that perseverance is not optional‚Äîit is essential.

Rain or shine, cold or heat, we row.
Headwinds, sidewinds, whitecaps‚Äîwe row.
Blisters on our hands, snot freezing on our faces‚Äîwe row.

We row because we choose to.

And that choice‚Äîto push through the discomfort, to silence the excuses, to find rhythm in the chaos‚Äîthat is what makes rowing more than just a sport. That is what makes it a life lesson.

Moving as One: The True Power of Rowing

There are plenty of tough sports‚Äîwrestling, cycling, cross-country running.
But what sets rowing apart?

Unity.

In an eight, every stroke must be identical. Every rower must feel the boat, feel the rhythm, feel each other‚Äôs energy.

Rowing is not just a physical test‚Äîit is a test of synchronization, of absolute trust.

You cannot hide in a rowing shell. There is no room for ego, no room for selfishness.

To row is to commit‚Äîfully, relentlessly‚Äîto something bigger than yourself.

And when you row for four years in high school, and then another four in college, you don‚Äôt just come out stronger‚Äîyou come out changed.

You emerge with an understanding of discipline, of teamwork, of grit‚Äîa level of resilience that most people will never experience.

And that, in my opinion, makes rowers some of the greatest unsung heroes in society.

The True Gift of Rowing: Perseverance

If there is one lesson I have taken from rowing, it is this:

Perseverance is everything.

Perseverance distracts you from self-doubt.
Perseverance drowns out negativity.
Perseverance keeps you moving forward when every muscle in your body wants to quit.

When we row, we persevere‚Äînot just against other boats, but against ourselves.

Rowing Camp Myths: Why Working With an Elite Online Rowing Coach is the Missing Link 

When parents think about rowing camps, they picture better performance, refined technique, and a boost in their child‚Äôs chances of success. But here‚Äôs the truth‚Äînot all rowing camps deliver on those promises.

As an Olympic Gold and Silver Medalist and the most successful online high school rowing coach, I‚Äôve seen firsthand the critical gaps in traditional rowing camps. The biggest? Camps completely ignore the connection between erg performance and on-water rowing technique‚Äîa link that‚Äôs essential for achieving elite results.

üö® Myth #1: Rowing Camps Improve Erg Scores
Most camps avoid ergs altogether. Why?

They focus only on on-water drills like seat racing or regatta simulations.
Many coaches (and rowers) hate ergs because they brutally expose flaws in fitness and technique.
Without structured erg training‚Äîlike targeted intervals or aerobic base-building‚Äîrowers actually lose progress.
The 2K erg score is a make-or-break metric for college recruitment, yet camps don‚Äôt prioritize it.

Limited personal attention: Camps have high coach-to-rower ratios, leaving athletes with minimal feedback.

snippet.title: Rowing Camp: Why choosing the right Rowing camp matters - Make every summer count.
snippet.description:
Why Choosing the Right Rowing Camp Matters: Make Every Summer Count

Time is precious for high school rowers aiming to get recruited to college. With limited summers to prepare, parents must carefully choose the right rowing camp to maximize their child‚Äôs potential. For men‚Äôs rowing, the summer before senior year is the final opportunity to submit a recruitable erg score. For women, however, recruiting often happens earlier, making it critical to focus on training during the summers before junior year.

No matter your child‚Äôs timeline, choosing the right camp can make all the difference in achieving their rowing goals.

The Freedom and Flexibility of Online Rowing Camps

My rowing camps are online programs, offering unparalleled flexibility. This means rowers can participate from anywhere in the world while balancing other commitments like internships, family time, or personal projects. Participants gain access to high-quality, personalized coaching without having to uproot their schedules.

With an online format, there‚Äôs no need to travel to a specific location, giving families the freedom to prioritize other aspects of life while still achieving elite-level training.

Key Questions to Ask When Choosing a Rowing Camp

Not all rowing camps are created equal. Parents should consider the following when selecting the right camp:
 ‚Ä¢ Does the camp focus on sculling, sweep rowing, or both?
 ‚Ä¢ Are they helping rowers improve their overall technique or just running physical conditioning drills?
 ‚Ä¢ Do they include training on mental preparedness and self-coaching skills?

The answers to these questions can help determine whether the camp aligns with your child‚Äôs specific goals and needs.

What Makes My Online Rowing Camps Unique?

At my online rowing camps, I provide a personalized, holistic training experience that prepares rowers for success on and off the water. Here‚Äôs what sets my programs apart:

1. Flexibility for Families and Rowers

Because my camps are online, participants can train from anywhere while having time to focus on other summer priorities. The program is tailored to their schedule, making it easy to balance elite training with personal growth and other commitments.

2. Conditioning and Heart Rate Training

I teach rowers to understand their bodies and how to train smarter, not harder. Learning to monitor heart rates and recovery is essential for maximizing performance and avoiding burnout.

3. Mental Preparedness and Visualization

Mental focus is critical for rowing success. I integrate visualization techniques and positive self-talk into the training process, helping rowers build confidence and stay calm under pressure.

4. Translating Erg Efficiency to Water Performance

I specialize in connecting rowing technique on the erg with performance on the water. This unique focus ensures that the skills rowers develop during training have a direct and measurable impact in competition.

5. Self-Coaching and Independent Problem-Solving

My programs empower rowers to evaluate their own technique using video analysis, mirrors, and innovative tools like resistance bands. This out-of-the-box thinking teaches participants how to self-correct and grow independently.

Why Your Child‚Äôs Training Timeline Matters

For men, the summer before senior year is the last opportunity to submit a recruitable erg score. Missing this window can severely limit recruiting opportunities.

For women, recruiting tends to happen earlier, which makes the summers before junior year especially critical. By focusing on training during these key years, rowers can ensure they‚Äôre putting their best foot forward when it counts most.

Is Your Child Ready for My Online Rowing Camp?

My online rowing camps are designed for motivated rowers ready to take their training‚Äîand their recruiting potential‚Äîto the next level. If you‚Äôre a parent interested in helping your child achieve their rowing goals, contact me today to see if they‚Äôre eligible for the program.

Don‚Äôt let the next summer slip away‚Äîinvest in your child‚Äôs rowing future today.
