For men‚Äôs rowing, the summer before senior year is the final opportunity to submit a recruitable erg score. For women, however, recruiting often happens earlier, making it critical to focus on training during the summers before junior year.

No matter your child‚Äôs timeline, choosing the right camp can make all the difference in achieving their rowing goals.

The Freedom and Flexibility of Online Rowing Camps

My rowing camps are online programs, offering unparalleled flexibility. This means rowers can participate from anywhere in the world while balancing other commitments like internships, family time, or personal projects. Participants gain access to high-quality, personalized coaching without having to uproot their schedules.

With an online format, there‚Äôs no need to travel to a specific location, giving families the freedom to prioritize other aspects of life while still achieving elite-level training.

Key Questions to Ask When Choosing a Rowing Camp

Not all rowing camps are created equal. Parents should consider the following when selecting the right camp:
 ‚Ä¢ Does the camp focus on sculling, sweep rowing, or both?
 ‚Ä¢ Are they helping rowers improve their overall technique or just running physical conditioning drills?
 ‚Ä¢ Do they include training on mental preparedness and self-coaching skills?

The answers to these questions can help determine whether the camp aligns with your child‚Äôs specific goals and needs.

What Makes My Online Rowing Camps Unique?

At my online rowing camps, I provide a personalized, holistic training experience that prepares rowers for success on and off the water. Here‚Äôs what sets my programs apart:

1. Flexibility for Families and Rowers

Because my camps are online, participants can train from anywhere while having time to focus on other summer priorities. The program is tailored to their schedule, making it easy to balance elite training with personal growth and other commitments.

2. Conditioning and Heart Rate Training

I teach rowers to understand their bodies and how to train smarter, not harder. Learning to monitor heart rates and recovery is essential for maximizing performance and avoiding burnout.

3. Mental Preparedness and Visualization

Mental focus is critical for rowing success. I integrate visualization techniques and positive self-talk into the training process, helping rowers build confidence and stay calm under pressure.

4. Translating Erg Efficiency to Water Performance

I specialize in connecting rowing technique on the erg with performance on the water. This unique focus ensures that the skills rowers develop during training have a direct and measurable impact in competition.

5. Self-Coaching and Independent Problem-Solving

My programs empower rowers to evaluate their own technique using video analysis, mirrors, and innovative tools like resistance bands. This out-of-the-box thinking teaches participants how to self-correct and grow independently.

Why Your Child‚Äôs Training Timeline Matters

For men, the summer before senior year is the last opportunity to submit a recruitable erg score. Missing this window can severely limit recruiting opportunities.

For women, recruiting tends to happen earlier, which makes the summers before junior year especially critical. By focusing on training during these key years, rowers can ensure they‚Äôre putting their best foot forward when it counts most.

Is Your Child Ready for My Online Rowing Camp?

My online rowing camps are designed for motivated rowers ready to take their training‚Äîand their recruiting potential‚Äîto the next level. If you‚Äôre a parent interested in helping your child achieve their rowing goals, contact me today to see if they‚Äôre eligible for the program.

Don‚Äôt let the next summer slip away‚Äîinvest in your child‚Äôs rowing future today.

snippet.title: Episode 22 Rowing Friends
snippet.description:
In this episode Kate expressed frustration about the changes to the live streaming service at the Saratoga Invitational rowing event, particularly the shift from a free to a paid service. She speculated that this change might be due to US Rowing contracting with a specific company for all rowing event live streams. Kate appealed to the organizers to reconsider this decision, given the importance of the live stream for remote viewers and the limitations of on-site viewing. They also shared their experiences with food tent setup, the importance of proper planning and organization for regatta events, and the challenges faced by coxswains in rowing boats. The conversation ended with their plans for the upcoming week, including finding someone to talk about food tents and coxins, and discussing the live stream issue and the need for easy access to it.






Please follow our podcast on your preferred listening platform and check us out on social.


This Podcast- @rowingfriendspod


Adrien- @rowingonthesquare


Kate- @ collegeadvisingbykate.

snippet.title: Return to Row Post Knee Surgery with Steve Tague
snippet.description:
In this episode, Steve shared his background in rowing, including his competitive achievements and transition to coaching, while discussing his ongoing recovery from knee replacement surgery and other injuries. He emphasized the importance of patience, community support, and adapting to new challenges in his fitness journey. The conversation also touched on the benefits of rowing as a low-impact exercise and the value of sharing personal experiences on social media, concluding with plans for a podcast release and future collaborations.

snippet.title: Episode 17 Rowing Friends Dan Anderson
snippet.description:
In this episode our special guest Dan Anderson discusses his background in rowing, his experiences in various regattas, and his journey into the sport. We also explored the challenges and opportunities of rowing on different bodies of water, the importance of maintaining connections with rowing club alumni, and the potential for a more recreational approach to the sport. Additionally, we touched on the topic of boathouse documentation, and Dan shared his experiences visiting over 300 boathouses. We also discussed the idea of a "return to row" campaign to engage former rowers.









Please follow our podcast on your preferred listening platform and check us out on socials.

snippet.title: Master Your Rowing Grip Tips for Better Performance! #shorts
snippet.description:
üí™ Master Your Rowing Grip for Strength and Power! üö£‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

One of the most common mistakes I see on the erg is a ùóπùóºùóºùòÄùó≤ ùó¥ùóøùó∂ùóΩ. 

While it's okay to have a relaxed hold, think about how weak it feels when you hang from a bar by your fingertips. üò¨

ùóüùóºùóºùòÄùó≤ ùó¥ùóøùó∂ùóΩ = ùòÑùó≤ùóÆùó∏ ùóΩùó≤ùóøùó≥ùóºùóøùó∫ùóÆùóªùó∞ùó≤.

To maximize strength and reduce strain on your finger flexors, you want a ùó∞ùóºùóªùòÅùóøùóºùóπùóπùó≤ùó± ùó¥ùóøùó∂ùóΩ with a ùó≥ùóπùóÆùòÅ ùòÑùóøùó∂ùòÄùòÅ and ùòÅùóµùòÇùó∫ùóØùòÄ ùòÇùóªùó±ùó≤ùóøùóªùó≤ùóÆùòÅùóµ the handle. üîë

A closed grip helps transfer power efficiently and avoids unnecessary stress on your forearms. 

It‚Äôs not about being overly tight; it's about being strong and secure! üí•

ùó•ùó≤ùó∫ùó≤ùó∫ùóØùó≤ùóø: A strong grip = a stronger stroke. üí™

snippet.title: Volume Management Key to Rowing Transition Success! #shorts
snippet.description:
üö£‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Transitioning from Water to Erg: What You Need to Know! üí•

After a long season on the water, it's tempting to jump straight into the rowing machine and replicate those same long distances, right? ü§î

But here's the thing: ùóúùóªùó±ùóºùóºùóø ùóøùóºùòÑùó∂ùóªùó¥ ùòÉùóºùóπùòÇùó∫ùó≤ ùó±ùóºùó≤ùòÄùóª‚ÄôùòÅ ùóÆùóπùòÑùóÆùòÜùòÄ ùòÅùóøùóÆùóªùòÄùóπùóÆùòÅùó≤ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùòÄùóÆùó∫ùó≤ ùòÑùóÆùòÜ ùóÆùòÄ ùòÑùóÆùòÅùó≤ùóø ùóøùóºùòÑùó∂ùóªùó¥. 

üí° You may be surprised at how many ‚Äúsneaky meters‚Äù you‚Äôve already accumulated throughout the season, especially if you‚Äôve been supplementing your on-water workouts with some erg training.

Before you dive into that 10K on the machine, take a moment to recalibrate your expectations and adjust your volume to match your body's needs. 

Tracking your meters can make all the difference! üß≠

ùó£ùóøùóº ùóßùó∂ùóΩ: Take it slow, especially when transitioning between the two, to avoid overloading your system. üõë

snippet.title: Transitioning from Water to Rowing Machine Avoid Injuries #shorts
snippet.description:
üö£‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Rowing on the Water vs. Rowing on the Erg üö£‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

Ever wonder why the transition from the water to the rowing machine feels off? It's all about the dynamics! üí•

On the water, we draw the boat underneath us with our bodies relatively stationary. But when we jump on the erg, the forces and momentum change completely. The footplate forces are higher, and the dynamics of the catch feel different‚Äîsometimes leading to those pesky injuries. üèãÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

üßê Fun fact: A lot of rowers say their back doesn't hurt on the water, but the machine can feel like a whole new world. That difference in force could be the culprit!

Stay injury-free with the right techniques for both! Let‚Äôs dive deeper into how you can transition smoothly between the two. üí™

#Rowing #ErgTraining #RowingTips #FitnessJourney #StayInjuryFree #RowingLife #RowingMachine #FitnessAfter50 #RowingTechnique

snippet.title: Plyometrics for Rowers: Jumps and Throws
snippet.description:
More about plyos: https://rowingstronger.com/2020/06/01/plyometrics-for-rowers/

snippet.title: Glute-Ham Raise (GHR)
snippet.description:
I like the GHR a lot with rowers to train an element of glute and hamstring strength that we miss from just rowing and erging. I typically begin with the Nordic hamstring curl and then progress to the GHR for 2-4 sets of 6-12 reps.

Progression: https://rowingstronger.substack.com/p/training-tip-nordic-hamstring-curl

Nordic hamstring curl: https://youtu.be/u8CEMBYXYkU

Recorded at the @Craftsbury Outdoor Center.

snippet.title: How I Coach the Hip Hinge for Rowers
snippet.description:
https://rowingstronger.com/2016/08/01/mastering-the-hip-hinge-for-rowing/

The hip hinge is a fundamental athletic movement, and rowing, erging, and sculling is no exception. For length on the recovery and power on the drive, master this movement on land first, learn to apply this skill when rowing, and strength train to improve performance.

snippet.description:
Read my article for more: https://rowingstronger.com/2022/03/26/scheduling-strength-training-with-rowing/

This is an excerpt from my presentation at the 2020 USRowing Convention. Learn how to schedule strength training to complement rowing training at the seasonal, weekly, and daily levels. This is important to maximize performance improvement from training and reduce risk of injury from fatigue spillover between modes of training.

snippet.title: USRowing: Return-to-Train for Masters Rowers
snippet.description:
April 29, 2021: I did a webinar with Liz Fusco, Director of Sports Nutrition at USRowing, discussing return-to-train for masters rowers. We discuss considerations for rowing technique, strength training, aerobic training, nutrition, and hydration given the needs of masters rowers racing 1ks in the summer weather and potential detraining due to pandemic restrictions.

FULL WEBINAR: https://youtu.be/jrbwN0HwWpA

Follow Liz Fusco: https://www.instagram.com/lizfoodco/

More return-to-train info at RowingStronger.com: https://rowingstronger.com/2020/05/11/rowing-return-to-train/

Check out my new project from 2020, Science of Rowing!
www.ScienceofRowing.com

snippet.title: Nordic Hamstring Curl Exercise for Rowers
snippet.description:
Article: https://rowingstronger.com/2021/10/18/nordic-hamstring-curl-rowing/

I've been using variations of this exercise more in my strength training for rowers and finding great results. The NHC trains the hamstrings through eccentric knee flexion, as well as the glutes via isometric hip extension. Be aware that this is an undertrained movement in rowing, and the eccentric emphasis can often result in high muscle soreness! Begin with just 3 sets of 5 using a 3-5-second lowering phase, and progress training load gradually from there.

[0:00] Base Variation: 5-second eccentric, assisted concentric
[0:37]: Common Errors
[1:56]: Band-Assisted Variation
[2:16]: Short-Range Variation
[2:45]: Partner Variation
[3:08]: Glute-Ham Raise Variation

snippet.title: 8 Ways to Use the Hex/Trap Bar for Rowers
snippet.description:
The hex/trap bar is my favorite deadlift variation for rowers. This video includes a general demonstration, the options of high handles or low handles, doing deadlifts with the hard-stop, touch-and-go, or full-reset style, as well as a few additional exercises you can do with a hex bar. 

Read more in my "Deadlifting for Rowing Complete Guide": https://rowingstronger.com/2019/01/07/deadlifting-for-rowing-complete-guide/

snippet.title: Rowing Power Training with Full Explosive Intent Strength Training
snippet.description:
We don't necessarily need to change exercises completely just to train with more emphasis on power. I find it more successful with rowers to modify the weight and tempo of the exercise to lift with full explosive intent.

More on training for power: https://rowingstronger.com/2015/08/24/peak-power-training-for-rowing/

snippet.title: Rp3 Rowing machine workout @ 16-18 30 minutes
snippet.description:
Description:
Experience a powerful low-stroke endurance session on the RP3 rowing machine! This 30-minute workout at 16‚Äì18 SPM (strokes per minute) focuses on rhythm, control, and building aerobic capacity. Perfect for rowers aiming to improve technique and endurance without spiking heart rate too early. Ideal for base training, recovery days, or technical refinement.

Stay consistent, focus on clean drive and smooth recovery, and let the flywheel teach you flow. Great for all levels!

‚∏ª

snippet.title: Final trail for asian game  üí™My best Rowing race effort behind the finish lineüö£|Never give up|
snippet.description:
On of the best race effort

‚ÄúIn an awe-inspiring display of determination and grit, I faced my best rowing race yet. At the start, I found myself trailing at the back of the pack, seemingly outmatched and behind my competitors. But with unwavering focus and relentless effort, I pushed through every stroke, steadily closing the gap. As the race progressed, I harnessed every ounce of strength and willpower, overtaking rowers one by one. In a thrilling finish, I surged past my rivals to claim first place, transforming what began as a daunting challenge into a triumphant victory. This race was a true testament to the power of perseverance and never giving up, no matter the odds.‚Äù

snippet.title: Rowing technique in slow motion üö£
snippet.description:
Rowing technique focuses on efficiency and coordination to maximize speed and minimize energy expenditure. It involves four main phases: the catch, drive, finish, and recovery. At the catch, the rower‚Äôs body is forward, with knees bent and arms extended, preparing for the stroke. The drive phase begins as the legs push against the footplate, followed by the body‚Äôs torso moving back, and finally, the arms pull the oar through the water. At the finish, the legs are extended, and the oars are fully drawn towards the body. During the recovery, the rower returns to the catch position by extending the arms first, followed by the torso and legs, maintaining a smooth, controlled motion. Effective technique emphasizes proper body posture, rhythm, and timing for maximum efficiency and power.

snippet.title: 2024 Australian Surf Boats National Team Selection Event
snippet.description:
Each year Surf Life Saving Australia and Surf Life Saving New Zealand select an Open Male, Open
Female, U23 Development Male & U23 Development Female surf boat crews to represent their country
in the annual Trans-Tasman Surf Boat Test Series.
The 2025 Trans-Tasman Surf Boat Test Series will be held on Saturday 8th February at Waihi Beach, New
Zealand with the 3-test series to be run alongside the NZ SLS North Island Surf Boat Championships.
To be considered for selection crews must enter via SEMS and attend the Australian Surf Boat Team
selection event at Ocean Beach on 6th December 2024. Note, your entry indicates your nomination for the
event.

snippet.title: Australian Surf Rowers League (ASRL) Sweeps Academy 2022
snippet.description:
The ASRL announced the formation of the ASRL Sweeps Academy to conduct nation-wide training for sweeps to prepare them for accreditation and improve skills. Headed up by Academy Manager Beck Hamilton, the Academy included 13 of the best sweep trainers in the country.

The Academy conducted its first course commencing in August 2022 for beginner S1 Sweeps, through to S2s/S3s wanting to improve their skills. The academy saw hundreds of new and emerging sweeps, with participants from every state. A combination of online and in person training allowed participants to gain information from different trainers around the country and obtain knowledge and experience to help them in their own sweep improvement. 

Sally Mac has created an incredible video showcasing the amazing efforts of our sweeps academy from last year. If you would like to be a part of our next sweeps academy, head to asrl.com.au and follow us on social media for all the information about our next sweeps academy. 

Head to https://asrl.com.au for more

snippet.title: 2021/22 ASRL President Nomination Video - Phil Chipman
snippet.description:
As you may know, we have one position, president, that requires a vote for the upcoming season.

We would like to introduce the candidates who have nominated for the position. This video is to support the nomination for Phil Chipman.

Voting is now open and will close on Saturday, 10th July at 1:00pm. All current Financial Members, Life Members and Hall of Fame Members have receive an email providing a unique link for access to the vote, controlled by our webmaster Perry Brennan. Members will be asked for a simple yes or no. To be the successful candidate for president a simple majority of votes is required.

If you have any questions regarding the process please email Natasha Tunney secretary@asrl.com.au

snippet.title: 2020 moment of reflection FINAL VERSION
snippet.description:
2020 Online Moment of Reflection

Each season at the Australian Surf Life Saving Championships, it has been our practice in the boat area, to pay our respects to those of the surf boat fraternity who have passed away since the previous season, called the 'Moment of Reflection'

This year, due to the cancellation of the 2020 Aussies, we are acknowledging those who have passed with a video via the ASRL website and social media channels, where we can still pause to quietly reflect on our surf boat mates.

We sincerely thank those who have assisted in providing the information and photos which has allowed us to prepare this presentation. A special mention to Mike Tamblyn ... this is his baby, and we are proud to continue the tradition in the modified format.

snippet.title: Vale - Ged Roods
snippet.description:
The surf boat community is in mourning after the death of Ged Roods, who passed away over the Easter weekend, aged 26.

Wording and images provided by Tony Kee.

Additional wording online at Port Macquarie News https://www.portnews.com.au/story/6720013/community-mourns-tragic-death-of-true-blue-ged-roods/

Ged rowed six seasons with Wauchope-Bonny Hills SLSC, including Juniors, Reserves and Open Male. This season he rowed with David Luck, Tony Kee, his best mate Mat Bird and they were swept by Manfred Sonntag. The crew name was Full Cassowary, and it was their second season together.

The crew had their best result at state titles this season, finishing in the top eight and missing the Surf Life Saving NSW Open Male Surf Boat Final in the closest of margins, and the crew were planning on making that final in 2021. Recently they held their own end of season rows and held their presentation via social media with Ged and his best mate 'Birdy' holding a mock surfboat race in a wheelbarrow.

Outside of Surfboats Ged was the President of the Wauchope Blues Rugby League Club for four years. He was a champion bloke for only 26 years old and had lived through a lot. His father Dan Roods also a rowed for Wauchope Bonny Hills and passed away in 2006.

Ged was known as an absolute larrikan, full of life, so reliable and an incredible athlete.

Ged is survived by his mother, Karen and siblings, older brother Aaron and younger sister Kristy.

The Australian Surf Rowers League, its members, and the wider surf boat community would like to pass on our condolences to the Roods family, Wauchope-Bonny Hills SLSC and wider Wauchope community.

AN OPEN LETTER BY TONY KEE, dated 12 April 2020

Dear Ged Roods

I have to write this as I can't bring myself to say it out loud. Ive had the privelege to know you for a long time now, we've rowed side by side for several seasons. It's a bit of a crazy sport, old Surfboat rowing.

I've heard it said that life is like Surfboats. We stand on the shore looking out, never sure what to expect but we take it on anyway, side by side. Some times we make it out clean, some times we get swamped and sometimes we catch the wave of the day from the turning cans and hit the beach first. And trust me mate we have done each of those many times!

They say your only ever as good as your last race so you will forever be a champion in my eyes. I dont know how we will ever be the same without you so I remember these words adapted by Wayne Gill which I used this afternoon as the sun sets on this day.

"I must go down to the sea today,
To the lonely sea and the sky.
Where I'll see you again old mate
In a Surfboat rowing by"

I know you'll be out there just over the horizon cracking waves with Buck, Stenno and your dad, Dan. And we all can't wait to see you again but we will cheers to you tonight and remember you forever!

RIP Ged Roods, the King of Wauchopeüëë ‚ù§üíô‚ù§

snippet.title: UM Rowing ‚ÄîA Thriving Community | Official launch of Quads¬†and¬†Doubles
snippet.description:
UM Rowing Club has launched new coastal rowing boats Quads and Doubles, the first of their kind in Malta.

As the world prepares to welcome Coastal Rowing as an Olympic Sport in 2028 and the  Commonwealth Games, the club being the first coastal rowing club in Malta has set further targets to compete in. These boats, the equipment and further investment will continue to support the thriving community not only in Malta but now also internationally.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The University of Malta Rowing Club (UM Rowing Club) is a student led sports club within the University of Malta which is open to all students, alumni and staff who show passion, commitment and respect towards the sport of rowing.

The club was established in October 2015 when a group of students, from different courses, joined together to form a Rowing Club which can represent the University of Malta in national and international events. Any student who wishes to start rowing, either for recreational purposes or as competitive sport, is welcome to join us and follow us on our socials. 

Become a member here: https://umrowingclub.org/join-us/‚Äã

Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/umrowingclub‚Äã
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/umrowing/‚Äã
Website: https://umrowingclub.org/‚Äã

snippet.title: Row For Lebanon - A 12 Hour Rowing Marathon
snippet.description:
üá±üáß Row for Lebanon - A 12 Hour Rowing Marathon üá±üáß

In December 2020, the Club, together with Lebanese Rowing Federation, IOC Young Leaders Malta, Maltese Olympic Committee and Tua Engineering Ltd.  managed to raise 975 euro to aid our fellow Lebanese rowers, after that the terrible blast of August 2020 destroyed their rowing space.

A massive thank you goes to all those who donated their money and time to row for this event to be a success üí™üí™

If you did not manage to donate you can still do so on www.rebuildrerow.com. üôè

Note: The event was done in December 2020, before the newly introduced Covid-19 measures.

snippet.title: Official Coastal Rowing Boats Inauguration
snippet.description:
The University of Malta Rowing Club is proud to announce the launch of the first coastal rowing boats in Malta. The University of Malta Rowing Club has purchased two C1X coastal rowing boats which were obtained through funding by the National Lotteries Good Causes Funds. These boats will serve to kickstart coastal rowing in Malta.

The coastal rowing boats were inaugurated today by Hon. Prof. Edward Scicluna and by Prof. Alfred Vella at University of Malta sports hall.  

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The club was established in October 2015 when a group of students, from different courses, joined together to form a Rowing Club which can represent the University of Malta in national and international events. Any student who wishes to start rowing, either for recreational purposes or as competitive sport, is welcome to join us and follow us on our socials. 

Become a member here: https://umrowingclub.org/join-us/

Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/umrowingclub
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/umrowing/
Email: uomrowing@gmail.com
Website: https://umrowingclub.org/

snippet.description:
In this video,Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton walks you through the 2 most common issues which occur at the beginning of the drive phase of the rowing stroke.  After discussing how and why these errors occur, coach Walton then details how to utilize the legs only drill to fix them both.  He also details WHY the drill is so effective when done properly, and what you should be aiming to feel each stroke.  If you're struggling with your drive mechanics, or even if you aren't, you will find value in this discussion.

snippet.title: Stop Toeing Off! Rowing Machine Technique Mistakes & Efficiency Tips
snippet.description:
This videos, taught by Olympian Luke Walton, can be valuable to anyone new to rowing, rowing with a team/club, looking for rowing machine workouts, training for CrossFit or Hyrox competitions, or anyone who who just wants to understand how to row the ‚Äúrower‚Äù (rowing machine) better.

In this video, Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton explains how toeing off at the front and/or backend of the rowing stroke will lead to decreased power, efficiency and speed on the rowing machine. Coach Walton walks you through how and why toeing off manifests in your rowing stroke, and how to go about fixing it. If you are struggling with toeing off, this video will give you the insights and focus to ensure you are rowing properly, allowing you to take your most efficient and powerful rowing strokes, every time.  

If you found this video helpful, don't forget to like, subscribe, and explore Rower Academy‚Äôs growing library of rowing tutorials. Stay tuned for more insightful content coming your way!

In this video, Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton explains how toeing off at the front and/or backend of the rowing stroke will lead to decreased power, efficiency and speed on the rowing machine. Coach Walton walks you through how and why toeing off manifests in your rowing stroke, and how to go about fixing it. If you are struggling with toeing off, this video will give you the insights and focus to ensure you are rowing properly, allowing you to take your most efficient and powerful rowing strokes, every time.

snippet.title: Rowing Machine Tip - Proper Body Swing Timing Boosts Drive Performance
snippet.description:
In this video, Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton discusses how proper timing and activation of the body during the drive phase of the rowing stroke on the rowing machine maximizes power, speed, and acceleration.  He then details how the legs, legs/body, legs/body/arms drill helps to enhance timing of your drive mechanics; and why mistiming of the drive sequence is detrimental to performance on the rowing machine.  If you are woking to maximize your drive mechanics, form, and technique on the rowing machine, this video is for you!

snippet.title: The SECRET to Super SECURE FOOT STRAPS on the ROWING MACHINE
snippet.description:
In this video, Coach and Olympian, Luke Walton walks you through a little known tip to ensure your foot straps stay secure, no matter the stroke rating or intensity with which you row.  Often times, as machines age, foot starts get worn and are prone to slipping.  With this little known loop, swoop, and pull trick, you'll be sure your feet stay secure, no matter what! At the same time, Coach Walton encourages you not to become reliant on the foot straps, and to make sure you are still rowing with a super engaged core, and maintaining power against the feet and handle through the entirety of your drive.  If your foot straps are slipping, or if you just want the highest level of security in your next high intensity effort, please give this video a watch.  

Channel Note:
These videos, taught by Olympian Luke Walton, can be valuable to anyone new to rowing, rowing with a team/club, anyone looking for rowing machine workouts, training for CrossFit or Hyrox competitions, or anyone who who just wants to understand how to row the ‚Äúrower‚Äù (rowing machine) better. snippet.title: Rowing Machine -  Master this Drill for Max Efficiency!
snippet.description:
This video is for rowers (novice and beyond) looking to maximize rowing form 

If you are struggling with your sequencing on the rowing stroke (specifically getting your body and handle past the knees on the recovery) the drills in this video will ensure you are rowing properly, allowing you to take your most efficient and powerful rowing strokes, every time.  

In this video, Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton explains the number one issue novice powers face on the rowing machine, and the best drills to correct it. Coach Walton walks you through the body over pause drill (a go to drill for coaches when it comes to correcting issues on the recovery).  He then speaks to his own favorite drill, the arms away pause (which addresses issues on the recovery even better than body over pause).  These drills (together and on their own) will help you to have your most efficient recovery each stroke, and prevent you from running into issues between the rowing machine handle and your knees.

Channel Note:
These videos, taught by Olympian Luke Walton, can be valuable to anyone new to rowing, rowing with a team/club, anyone looking for rowing machine workouts, training for CrossFit or Hyrox competitions, or anyone who who just wants to understand how to row the ‚Äúrower‚Äù (rowing machine) better.  If you found this video helpful, don't forget to like, subscribe, and explore Rower Academy‚Äôs growing library of rowing tutorials. Stay tuned for more insightful content coming your way!

snippet.title: Rowing Machine Form: Avoid These 2 Common Arm Activation Errors
snippet.description:
In this video, rowing Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton discusses the 2 most common errors when it comes to the arm draw on the drive of the rowing machine stroke: 1) grabbing at the front end and 2) yanking at the back end.  Coach Walton then goes on to equip you with 2 drills to correct your arm activation and draw issues: 1) Legs, Legs/Body, Full Strokes and 2) Close Grip Rowing.  If overworking the arms is an issue for you in your rowing stroke, then this discussion is for you!  You'll leave this video with a clear understanding of what the arm issues are, why they are harmful to the efficiency of your stoke, and what to do in order to correct your rowing technique.  

Channel Note:
These videos, taught by Olympian Luke Walton, can be valuable to anyone new to rowing, rowing with a team/club, anyone looking for rowing machine workouts, training for CrossFit or Hyrox competitions, or anyone who who just wants to understand how to row the ‚Äúrower‚Äù (rowing machine) better.  

If you found this video helpful, don't forget to like, subscribe, and explore Rower Academy‚Äôs growing library of rowing tutorials. Stay tuned for more insightful content coming your way!

snippet.localized.title: Rowing Machine Form: Avoid These 2 Common Arm Activation Errors
snippet.localized.description:
In this video, rowing Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton discusses the 2 most common errors when it comes to the arm draw on the drive of the rowing machine stroke: 1) grabbing at the front end and 2) yanking at the back end.  Coach Walton then goes on to equip you with 2 drills to correct your arm activation and draw issues: 1) Legs, Legs/Body, Full Strokes and 2) Close Grip Rowing.  If overworking the arms is an issue for you in your rowing stroke, then this discussion is for you!  You'll leave this video with a clear understanding of what the arm issues are, why they are harmful to the efficiency of your stoke, and what to do in order to correct your rowing technique.

snippet.title: Avoid OVER COMPRESSION on the ROWING MACHINE with These Tips
snippet.description:
In the video, Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton walks you through what "over compression" is, what causes it, and how to ensure you avoid it while still maintaining free long roll into the front end of the rowing stroke.  Over compression is bad, but full compression is still good.  So you want to make sure you aren't shortening your stroke when working to prevent over compression.  With proper foot position and drills, supplied to you by Coach Walton, you can still roll plenty far into the front end before over compressing.  Understanding the dos and don't of compression at the catch is key to creating your most efficient, long, and powerful rowing strokes

00:26 What is ‚ÄúOver Compression‚Äù on the Rowing Machine?
02:32 Two Main Causes of Over Compression
03:00 Issue One: Poor Set Up After the Finish
04:36 Issue Two: Rower Foot Height Setting Too Low
06:20 Legs Only Rowing Drill for Proper Compression

snippet.title: ROWING at 24 SPM - Unlock Your Perfect Rhythm & Power on the Machine!
snippet.description:
Maximize Your Rowing Stroke Rating with this min. on / min. off Rating Ladder

If you are struggling to keep your strokes long, strong, and smooth as the stroke rating increases,  this video will ensure you are rowing those higher rates properly, allowing you to take your most efficient and powerful rowing strokes, regardless of spm, every time.  

In this video, Olympian and Coach, Luke Walton explains why rowing higher stroke ratings can be more difficult than lower ones, especially when it comes to completing each stroke, and keeping the fan spinning on the rowing machine as fast as possible. Coach Walton walks you through a rating ladder of minute on, minute off rowing, with increasing stroke rating each piece.  This drill/workout will help you to generate your most connected, efficient, and powerful rowing strokes, regardless of stroke rating, and especially at higher rates.
